<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-921-968  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 921 968.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Computing  Sept 1989 p23(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Measuring factory performance. (yield, throughput, waste, qualityand inventory are the new yardsticks)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The determination of manufacturing performance and costs (andeventual product price) in advanced factory environments involvessuch factors as quality, activity, total output (and per employeeoutput), return on investment and 'true product cost' analyses.andO;Traditional cost accounting measurements, particularly thelabor-related ones, are no longer generally accepted as viablefactors.andP;  This is particularly true because the speed of productand manufacturing change results in more rapid fluctuations inreal costs, often measured in days.andP;  The implementing ofcomputer-aided costing systems enable the modeling of a variety ofmanufacturing costs, but such systems may be more use as modelingtools that can be combined with management judgements.andP;  The focusof such tools is ever more on ensuring that the manufacturingprocess is optimal.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TrendsCost EstimationComputer-Aided ManufacturingFactory ManagementAutomationPerformance ImprovementCost Reduction.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>